#PIVOT_WIDER and #PIVOT_LONGER

#from wide to long format

data <- data.frame(ID1 = LETTERS[1:4],        # Create example data
                   ID2 = rep(letters[1:3], each = 4),
                   measure_1 = 1:12,
                   measure_2 = 21:32)
data                                          # Print example data
##    ID1 ID2 measure_1 measure_2
## 1    A   a         1        21
## 2    B   a         2        22
## 3    C   a         3        23
## 4    D   a         4        24
## 5    A   b         5        25
## 6    B   b         6        26
## 7    C   b         7        27
## 8    D   b         8        28
## 9    A   c         9        29
## 10   B   c        10        30
## 11   C   c        11        31
## 12   D   c        12        32
# Install & load tidyr package
library("tidyr")
 # Convert wide to long
data_long <- pivot_longer(data = data,       
                          cols = c("measure_1", "measure_2"))
data_long   
## # A tibble: 24 × 4
##    ID1   ID2   name      value
##    <chr> <chr> <chr>     <int>
##  1 A     a     measure_1     1
##  2 A     a     measure_2    21
##  3 B     a     measure_1     2
##  4 B     a     measure_2    22
##  5 C     a     measure_1     3
##  6 C     a     measure_2    23
##  7 D     a     measure_1     4
##  8 D     a     measure_2    24
##  9 A     b     measure_1     5
## 10 A     b     measure_2    25
## # ℹ 14 more rows

#from long to wide format

data_wide <- pivot_wider(data = data_long)    # Convert long to wide
data_wide                                     # Print wide data

#JOIN DATA: you have to have at least 1 column that match

df1 = data.frame(CustomerId = c(1:6), Product = c(rep("Toaster", 3), rep("Radio", 3)))
df1
##   CustomerId Product
## 1          1 Toaster
## 2          2 Toaster
## 3          3 Toaster
## 4          4   Radio
## 5          5   Radio
## 6          6   Radio
df2 = data.frame(CustomerId = c(2, 4, 6), State = c(rep("Alabama", 2), rep("Ohio", 1)))
df2
##   CustomerId   State
## 1          2 Alabama
## 2          4 Alabama
## 3          6    Ohio
#inner
inner_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product   State
## 1          2 Toaster Alabama
## 2          4   Radio Alabama
## 3          6   Radio    Ohio
#left outer
left_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product   State
## 1          1 Toaster    <NA>
## 2          2 Toaster Alabama
## 3          3 Toaster    <NA>
## 4          4   Radio Alabama
## 5          5   Radio    <NA>
## 6          6   Radio    Ohio
#right outer
right_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product   State
## 1          2 Toaster Alabama
## 2          4   Radio Alabama
## 3          6   Radio    Ohio
#full join
full_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product   State
## 1          1 Toaster    <NA>
## 2          2 Toaster Alabama
## 3          3 Toaster    <NA>
## 4          4   Radio Alabama
## 5          5   Radio    <NA>
## 6          6   Radio    Ohio
#keep only observations in df1 that match in df2.
semi_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product
## 1          2 Toaster
## 2          4   Radio
## 3          6   Radio
#drop all observations in df1 that match in df2 (2-4-6), keep the observations do not match (1-3-5).
anti_join(df1, df2)
## Joining with `by = join_by(CustomerId)`
##   CustomerId Product
## 1          1 Toaster
## 2          3 Toaster
## 3          5   Radio
#merge only keep what match- 
merge(df1, df2)
##   CustomerId Product   State
## 1          2 Toaster Alabama
## 2          4   Radio Alabama
## 3          6   Radio    Ohio

#VISUALIZATION

library(ggplot2)

#Histogram

ggplot(data = cars, aes(x = speed)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "salmon")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(data = cars, aes(x = dist)) +
  geom_histogram(fill = "blue") +
  theme_minimal()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

#Bar_plot

ggplot(data = cars, aes(x = speed)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "salmon")

ggplot(data = cars, aes(x = speed)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "blue")

#boxplot

ggplot(data = mtcars) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = "", y = mpg)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = "", y = disp), fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of MPG and Disp",
       y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal()

#boxplots for many variables

#group of variables 
variables <- c("mpg", "disp", "hp", "drat", "cyl")
#boxplot
ggplot(data = reshape2::melt(mtcars[, variables])) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(x = variable, y = value)) +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Selected Variables in mtcars",
       x = "Variable",
       y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal()
## No id variables; using all as measure variables

#mpg: mile per gallon 
#engine displacement (capacity)
#hp: horsepower 
#drat: rear axle ratio
#cyl:cylinders

#scatte plot

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) +
  geom_point()

#add a regression line to explain the data

ggplot(data = mtcars, aes(x = mpg, y = hp)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of MPG vs. HP with Regression Line",
       x = "Miles per Gallon",
       y = "Horsepower") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
